keholders, and strange bedfellow alliances. These intriguing and complex dynamics are indicative of a longer, twenty-year shift in which the movement became nationalized and mainstreamed. Using in-depth interviews with major players in the national movement, formerly incarcerated activists, celebrities, and donors, this is the first book to turn the mirror back on the criminal justice reform movement itself—the frames used, the voices heard, the capital activated among elite participants, and the bitter controversies. This snapshot in time raises much larger questions about how our democratic processes inform criminal justice policy, and where we are going in the decades to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCorrectional lawzUnited States2DLC. 0aCorrectional lawzUnited States. 0aImprisonmentzUnited States2DLC. 0aImprisonmentzUnited States. 0aLaw reformzUnited States2DLC. 0aLaw reformzUnited States. 0aPrisonersxDeinstitutionalizationzUnited States. 0aSentences (Criminal procedure)zUnited States2DLC. 0aSentences (Criminal procedure)zUnited States. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / General.2bisacsh  aCriminal Justice Reform.  aLegal Reform.  aMass Incarceration.  aNonprofits.  aPhilanthropy.  aPolitical Movements.  aSocial Change.  aSocial Justice.  aSocial Movements.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2023 Englishz978311131914808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2023z9783111318226oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uht